\section secParallelRenderingWithParaView Parallel Rendering with ParaView

<strong>Prerequisite</strong>:
<a href="http://paraview.org/">ParaView</a> (client) is installed on your 
local machine, and <em>ParaView</em> (server; with MPI support) is installed 
on the machine which is intended as rendering server.

<strong>Important</strong>:
The version of the client must match that of the server!

For a local installation of <em>ParaView</em> on the rendering server see 
\ref secInstallParaView.

This mode of running <em>ParaView</em> is also called "Client-Server mode".
In client-server mode, one executes the <tt>pvserver</tt> program on a parallel 
machine and connect to it with the <em>ParaView</em> client application.

<ol>
  <li>
    Start the ParaView server on the rendering server, e.g. <tt>cekon</tt>, 
    with your local machine as client (the parameter <tt>-ch</tt> describes 
    the "client host"):
    \verbatim
    salloc -n <NP> mpirun /usr/local/bin/pvserver -ch=<yourlocalhost>.gcsc.uni-frankfurt.de -rc --use-offscreen-rendering
    \endverbatim
    The option <tt>-rc</tt> stands for "reverse connection".
    This means that the server connects to the client instead of the client 
    connecting to the server.
    This may be necessary when the server is behind a firewall.
  </li>
  <li>Start the ParaView client on your local machine as usual.</li>
  <li>Then choose "File --> Connect".
    In the new dialog "Choose Server Configuration" click "Add Server" 
    (window title changes to "Edit Server Configuration").

    Fill in the necessary informations to define a connection to the ParaView 
    server running on <tt>cekon</tt>:
    <ul>
      <li>Name: "cekon" (only descriptive; this is the name that will appear 
        in the "Choose Server Configuration" dialog),
      <li>Server Type: "Client / Server (reverse Connection)",
      <li>Port: "11111" (if default port can be used; see below).
    </ul>
    Then click "Configure" and choose "Startup Type": "Manual". Click "Save"

    Select the (newly defined) server and click "Connect".
  </li>
  <li>In the "Pipeline Browser" of your client choose the server as "data object"

<!--
    \todo Test and explicate selection of server in pipeline browser.
-->

  </li>
</ol>

If a ParaView server is already running and listening at the default port, 
<tt>11111</tt> (or this port is blocked by a firewall etc.), you have to start 
the server using a non-default port using the additional parameter 
<tt>--server-port=&lt;portnumber&gt;</tt> (and of course take this into account 
also when connecting from the client to the server).

For some further documentation see e.g.:
- http://www.paraview.org/Wiki/Setting_up_a_ParaView_Server#Running_the_Server
